definition.value: A thienopyridine that is 4,5,6,7-tetrahydrothieno[3,2-c]pyridine in which the hydrogen attached to the nitrogen is replaced by an o-chlorobenzyl group, the methylene hydrogen of which is replaced by a  methoxycarbonyl group (the S enantiomer). A P2Y12 receptor antagonist, it is used to inhibit blood clots and prevent heart attacks.
Any organic heterobicyclic compound whose skeleton results from the formal ortho-fusion of any bond of a pyridine with any bond of a thiophene.

A multi-component mixture comprising mostly of colistin A (R = Me) and B (R = H), with small amounts of colistin C and other polymyxins, produced by certain strains of Bacillus polymyxa var. colistinus. An antibiotic, it is used as its sulfate salt (for oral or topical use) or as the sodium salt of the N-methylsulfonic acid derivative (the injectable form) in the treatment of severe Gram-negative infections, partiularly those due to Pseudomonas aeruginosa.
Any carbohydrate sulfate that is a polysaccharide carrying at least one O-sulfo substituent.
A kanamycin that is kanamycin B lacking the 3- and 4-hydroxy groups on the 2,6-diaminosugar ring.
An aryl sulfate that is dopamine in which the phenolic hydrogen at position 3 has been replaced by a sulfo group.
A spiro compound in which at least one of the cyclic components is an oxygen heterocyle.
A cobalt corrinoid that is precorrin-8 in which the four pyrrole-type nitrogens are bound to a central cobalt atom.
H1-receptor antagonists are the drugs that selectively bind to but do not activate histamine H1 receptors, thereby blocking the actions of endogenous histamine.
Histamine antagonists are the drugs that bind to but do not activate histamine receptors, thereby blocking the actions of histamine or histamine agonists.
Drugs used for their actions on histaminergic systems.
A cobalt-corrinoid hexaamide that is the parent compound of the class of cobamides.

Cyanine dyes are synthetic dyes with the general formula R2N[CH=CH]nCH=N(+)R2    <-> R2N(+)=CH[CH=CH]nNR2 (n is a small number) in which the nitrogen and part of the conjugated chain usually form part of a heterocyclic system, such as imidazole, pyridine, pyrrole, quinoline and thiazole.
H2-receptor antagonists are the drugs that selectively bind to but do not activate histamine H2 receptors, thereby blocking the actions of endogenous histamine.
Any agent that acts on an adrenergic receptor or affects the life cycle of an adrenergic transmitter.
Any of a class of cyclic chemical compounds that contain an unsaturated six-membered ring with one ring oxygen atom and an oxo substituent.
The simplest member of the class of 2-pyranones that is 2H-pyran with an oxo substituent at position 2.
A pyranone that is 4H-pyran substituted by an oxo group at position 4.
The stable isotope of aluminium with relative atomic mass 26.98153 and nuclear spin (5)/2.
The radioactive isotope of aluminium with relative atomic mass 25.986892 and half-life of 717,000 years.
The radioactive isotope of aluminium with relative atomic mass 27.981910 and half-life of 2.25 min.
The stable isotope of phosphorus with relative atomic mass 30.973762 and nuclear spin (1)/2.
The radioactive isotope of phosphorus with relative atomic mass 31.973907 and half-life of 14.26 days.
The radioactive isotope of phosphorus with relative atomic mass 32.971725, half-life of 25.34 days and nuclear spin (1)/2.
The stable isotope of silicon with relative atomic mass 28.9764947, 4.683 atom percent natural abundancy, and nuclear spin (1)/2.
The stable isotope of silicon with relative atomic mass 27.9769265. The most abundant (92.23 atom percent) isotope of naturally occurring silicon.
The stable isotope of silicon with relative atomic mass 29.9737702. The least abundant (3.09 atom percent) isotope of naturally occurring silicon.
The radioactive isotope of silicon with relative atomic mass 30.975363, half-life of 2.62 hours and nuclear spin (3)/2.
The radioactive isotope of silicon with relative atomic mass 31.974148. The longest-lived silicon radionuclide with half-life of 172 years.
The stable isotope of sulfur with relative atomic mass 31.972071. The most abundant (95.02 atom percent) isotope of naturally occurring sulfur.
The stable isotope of sulfur with relative atomic mass 32.9714585, 0.75 atom percent natural abundance, and nuclear spin (3)/2.
The stable isotope of sulfur with relative atomic mass 33.9678668 and 4.21 atom percent natural abundance.
The stable isotope of sulfur with relative atomic mass 35.9670809. The least abundant (0.02 atom percent) isotope of naturally occurring sulfur.
The radioactive isotope of sulfur with relative atomic mass 34.9690322 and nuclear spin (3)/2. The longest-lived sulfur radionuclide with half-life of 87.5 days.
The radioactive isotope of sulfur with relative atomic mass 36.9711257 and  half-life of 5.05 min.
The radioactive isotope of sulfur with relative atomic mass 37.97116 and half-life of 170.3 min.
A glycodiaosylceramide having 3-O-sulfo-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucose as the disaccharide component and N-acylsphingosine as the sphingoid base.
